  "script": "This is the tallest waterslide ever built, and riding it is closer to falling than sliding. It stands taller than a 17-story building, and you drop almost straight down before the track flattens out at the bottom. Engineers had to test it with sandbags and dummies first, because the speed was hard to predict: too light and you fly off the curve, too heavy and you slam into it. Riders hit speeds over 60 miles an hour in just a few seconds. One famous version was so dangerous it had to be torn down. Builders keep chasing the record anyway, stacking the towers higher every single year. So how tall can a waterslide get before physics says no?",
